ce:section.ce:para:
The antioxidant capacity of CDs is typically evaluated using reactive species that do not have biological relevance, such as DPPH. In this work, CD-L was evaluated against two reactive species of biological importance, O2
                        •− and HOCl, respectively (Table 1
                        ). Their antioxidant activity is mainly directed towards scavenging HOCl, with an IC50 value close to that of quercetin, the positive standard used and, as far as we know, it is the first report of elimination of this reactive species by CDs. HOCl is the main strong oxidant generated by neutrophils and is a potent microbicidal agent. At high concentrations, however, this can lead to the formation of chlorinated derivatives such as chloramines, which interfere with protein folding and cause protein aggregation and are mainly related to the development and progression of neurodegenerative diseases [38].
